<p>Planning a trip to <strong>Little Boracay in Calatagan, Batangas</strong>? This complete guide covers everything you need — drive directions from Manila, the boat transfer process, what to bring, and a sample day trip itinerary so you make the most of your visit.</p>

<h2>How Far is Little Boracay from Manila?</h2>
<p>Little Boracay is located in <strong>Calatagan, Batangas</strong>, approximately <strong>130–150 kilometres south of Metro Manila</strong>. Under normal traffic conditions, the drive takes <strong>3 to 4 hours</strong>. On weekends and long weekends, expect heavier traffic on SLEX — leaving before 6 AM is strongly recommended.</p>

<h2>Step-by-Step Directions from Manila to Little Boracay</h2>

<h3>Step 1 — Take SLEX South</h3>
<p>From Metro Manila, enter the <strong>South Luzon Expressway (SLEX)</strong> heading south. SLEX connects directly to the STAR Tollway, which is the main expressway toward Batangas. Toll fees apply — bring your EasyCard or prepare exact change for cash lanes.</p>

<h3>Step 2 — STAR Tollway toward Batangas</h3>
<p>Continue on the <strong>STAR Tollway</strong> (Southern Tagalog Arterial Road) heading toward Batangas. The tollway exits toward various Batangas destinations — you'll be heading toward the Lian/Nasugbu/Balayan direction which leads to Calatagan.</p>

<h3>Step 3 — Exit toward Lian and Navigate to Calatagan</h3>
<p>Exit the tollway toward <strong>Lian, Batangas</strong>. From the exit, follow the road through Lian town and continue toward <strong>Calatagan Municipality</strong>. Use <strong>Google Maps or Waze</strong> — search "Little Boracay Calatagan" for the most direct routing to the jump-off area. Total distance from the toll exit to Calatagan is approximately 25–35 kilometres.</p>

<h3>Step 4 — Reach the Boat Jump-Off Point</h3>
<p>Navigate to the coastal barangays of Calatagan where local boat operators offer transfers to the Little Boracay sandbar. <strong>Contact operators in advance</strong> to confirm pickup location, as jump-off points can vary. Book your floating cottage ahead of time — especially on weekends.</p>

<h3>Step 5 — Boat Transfer to the Sandbar</h3>
<p>The boat ride to Little Boracay sandbar takes approximately <strong>10–20 minutes</strong> depending on conditions and your jump-off point. Boats typically run from early morning until early afternoon. Always confirm with operators the day before — boats may not operate in rough weather or during unusually high tides.</p>

